name: AWS S3
description: This app integrates with AWS S3 to perform investigative actions

use_role.description: Use attached role when running Phantom in EC2

actions.description: Validate the asset configuration for connectivity using supplied configuration
List all buckets configured on S3

actions.verbose: The bucket will be created in the region specified in the asset configuration. The bucket name provided has to be unique and it should not be already used in the AWS S3 globally.

The tags parameter takes a JSON dictionary containing the tags that will be given to the specified bucket. The dictionary should have the format:

{
    "tag1_key": "tag1_value",
    "tag2_key": "tag2_value"
    ...
}

The grants parameter takes a dictionary where each key is a canonical user ID and each value is one of the following permissions:
  • FULL_CONTROL
  • WRITE
  • WRITE_ACP
  • READ
  • READ_ACP
An example JSON object would be:

{
    "111a11a11aa1111111aa11aaa1111a111a1aa111111a1a1a11aa11aa11a11aa1": "FULL_CONTROL",
    "222b22b22bb2222222bb22bbb2222b222b2bb222222b2b2b22bb22bb22b22bb2": "READ"
}

The owner parameter takes the canonical ID of an AWS user. This parameter must be provided if the grants parameter is included (even if there is no desire to change the owner; in this case, just provide the ID of the current owner of the bucket).

WARNING: Calling this action will replace the bucket's current tags and permissions with the tags and permission supplied to this action. To avoid overwriting the bucket's present data, first run get bucket to get the current tag and permission dictionaries, then add new tags and grants to those dictionaries before calling this action.

tags.description: JSON dictionary containing tags to give object

kms_key.description: KMS Key (Only if encryption is AWS:KMS)

grants.description: JSON dictionary of users and the permissions to grant them

actions.verbose:
This action will list all objects in the given bucket. It will recursively list all objects in each folder in the bucket as well.

If given the key parameter, the action will start listing objects at the given key (which could include objects at the same level as the specified key). The key must be a full path from the root of the bucket.

The limit parameter has a maximum value of 1000. If no limit is provided, it will default to 1000. If more objects than the specified limit exist, the action will return a NextContinuationToken. To get the next batch of objects, pass this token in a new action as the continuation_token.

limit.description: Max number of objects to list

continuation_token.description: Use this parameter to get the next set of objects from a previous action

actions.verbose: If the download_file parameter is set to true, this action will download the specified file to the vault. The downloaded file will be given a name matching the given key.

The tags parameter takes a JSON dictionary containing the tags that will be given to the specified key in the specified bucket. The dictionary should have the format:

{
    "tag1_key": "tag1_value",
    "tag2_key": "tag2_value"
    ...
}

The grants parameter takes a dictionary where each key is a canonical user ID and each value is one of the following permissions:
  • FULL_CONTROL
  • WRITE
  • WRITE_ACP
  • READ
  • READ_ACP
An example JSON object would be:

{
    "111a11a11aa1111111aa11aaa1111a111a1aa111111a1a1a11aa11aa11a11aa1": "FULL_CONTROL",
    "222b22b22bb2222222bb22bbb2222b222b2bb222222b2b2b22bb22bb22b22bb2": "READ"
}

The owner parameter takes the canonical ID of an AWS user. This parameter must be provided if the grants parameter is included (even if there is no desire to change the owner; in this case, just provide the ID of the current owner of the object).

WARNING: Calling this action will replace the object's current tags and permissions with the tags and permission supplied to this action. To avoid overwriting the object's present data, first run get object to get the current tag and permission dictionaries, then add new tags and grants to those dictionaries before calling this action.
